{
  "doc_id": "31159",
  "text": "As previously noted, there were no maternal factors significantly associated with Hb in the infants at age 6 months in the controlled linear regression model. In a previous study on 990 infants in rural Indonesia [CITATION_1] , the authors found that 3-to 5-month-old infants born to anaemic mothers had significantly lower Hb concentrations than infants born to non-anaemic mothers. However, the authors did not specify at what point during the pregnancy Hb was measured in the mothers. The relationship between maternal haematological status during pregnancy and that of her infant has long been controversial, with some studies suggesting no association [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] while others report a positive relationship [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . It is feasible that Hb status in pregnancy would impact on anaemia prevalence in infants. Over 50 % of maternal anaemia in the world is due to Fe deficiency [CITATION_8] . The placenta is rich in transferrin receptors thus facilitating the transfer of Fe from the maternal to the fetal side of the placenta, often at the expense of the mother [CITATION_9] . However, if the mother is severely Fe-depleted, it is highly likely that the net transfer of Fe will be affected [CITATION_10] . On the other hand, the fact that no association was observed between infant and maternal Hb in the current study more than likely reflects the fact that none of the mothers was severely anaemic.",
